export const frontmatter = {
  title: "French history",
  languages: ["en"],
  language: "en",
  intro: "Preparing for the French nationality interview",
  publishedDate: new Date("2024-07-16").toISOString(),
};
---

<Article frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <section>
    <h3>Context</h3>
    <p>
      This really is a tool for me to use, but feel free to use it too! I&#39;m
      in the process of applying for French nationality, which is honestly just
      a lot of waiting (which makes me anxious). I know I should be using this
      time to brush up on my French history, knowing that I could be asked about
      any of these people/events in the interview. In interviews, I often freeze
      so it&#39;s important that I prepare in advance to minmise this risk.
    </p>
    <p>
      I&#39;m not good at deciding what to work on, so I&#39;m simplifying the
      decision - there will be a random person, event and fast response
      generated each time the page is refreshed. The goal is to spent time each
      day researching or revising based on the generated responses.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is based on the <em>livret du citoyen</em> and interview questions that
      I have seen. This will not cover everything, but it&#39;s a place to start
      and I will continue adding to the lists. It&#39;s important to note that there
      will always be person questions such as why you want to become French and your
      life in France.
    </p>
  </section>
  <button class="cta" type="button" id="button-generate">generate new</button>
  <section>
    <h3>
      person: <output id="output-people">
        {people[Math.floor(Math.random() * people.length)]}
      </output>
    </h3>
    <p>People who are important in French history. Things to consider:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>why are they important?</li>
      <li>what time period are they from?</li>
      <li>what are they most known for?</li>
    </ul>

    <hr />
  </section>
  <section>
    <h3>
      event: <output id="output-events">
        {events[Math.floor(Math.random() * events.length)]}
      </output>
    </h3>
    <p>Events to know in details:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>what year(s) did the event occur in?</li>
      <li>what triggered the event?</li>
      <li>what known people were involved in the event?</li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
  </section>
  <section>
    <h3>
      fast responses: <output id="output-fast-responses">
        {fastResponses[Math.floor(Math.random() * fastResponses.length)]}
      </output>
    </h3>
    <p>
      Questions/themes that require simplier answers, often a definition or
      knowing the stat.
    </p>
    <p>Things to consider:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>how does this tie into other important events?</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <script define:vars={{ people, events, fastResponses }}>
    const outputPeople = document.getElementById("output-people");
    const outputEvents = document.getElementById("output-events");
    const outputFastResponses = document.getElementById(
      "output-fast-responses",
    );
    document.getElementById("button-generate").addEventListener("click", () => {
      outputPeople.innerText =
        people[Math.floor(Math.random() * people.length)];
      outputEvents.innerText =
        events[Math.floor(Math.random() * events.length)];
      outputFastResponses.innerText =
        fastResponses[Math.floor(Math.random() * fastResponses.length)];
    });
  </script>
</Article>
